710640f-a.text:
Eleventh Ave., south from Wiest 35th Street, showing work progresSing on the track removal project of the New York Central Railroad at this point. Note the steel bridgelike structure on the easterly side of the thoroughfare that will raise this Avenue ten feet above its former level and permit the railroad tracks to pass underneath.connecting the trackage in the rock cut with the yard layout on the westerly side of the Avenue. Appearing on the left, at the N.E. corner of the Avenue and West 35th Street is the old R.H. Macy Warehouse undergoing structural renovation to further this work and permit freight handling facilities to its future tenants
under Railroad ownership.
1937.
qift of New York Central System
Ruublicity Bureau.

710646f-a.text:
EEleventh Ave. (foreground), at the N.E. corner of West 35th Street (rigdt), showing the front of the old R.H. Macy warehouse being supported by a new foundation to permit the New York Central Rai lroad tracks to pass beneath. The street levels on both sides are being elevated about 10 feet so that the former second story is now the first.
1937.
Gift of New York Central System
Publicity Bureau.

710647f-a.text:
Eleventh Ave. (right), at the N.E. corner of West 35th Street (left), showing a rear view of the Macy warehouse ai this location. This structure stands on a new steel and concrete foundation between which the main tracks of the New York Central Railroad will pass to connect with the loop and yard tracks beyond. Note also the new raised street and avenue levels, same being elevated about 10 feet. The photographer is viewing in a southwestward direction from 36th
Street, eastward of Eleventh Ave.
1937.
Cift of New York Central Railway System
Publicity Bureau.

710648f-a.text:
Eleventh Ave. (right), at the N.E. corner of West 35th Street (left), showing a rear view of the Macy warehouse at this location. A new foundation is being installed under this structure to permit the New York Central Railroad tracks to pass under it at various angles and elevations and to equip it with an outside elevator and a 5 car sidetrack and freight platform. The streets in front and alongside were elevated ten feet, so that the former second floor was promoted to
the first.
July 24, 1937.
Gift of New Yorl Central System
Publicity Bureau.
